00:00:00.780 --> 00:00:03.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:23.040 --> 00:00:24.340
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Hi.

00:00:24.340 --> 00:00:27.200
My name is Larry Appelbaum from the
Music Division here at the Library

00:00:27.200 --> 00:00:32.180
of Congress, and I'm pleased to say
joining us is composer, arranger,

00:00:32.180 --> 00:00:33.830
band leader, Maria Schneider.

00:00:33.830 --> 00:00:35.130
Nice to see you again.

00:00:35.130 --> 00:00:36.430 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Good to see you.

00:00:36.430 --> 00:00:38.810
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Yeah, we
spent some time this morning going

00:00:38.810 --> 00:00:43.280
through some treasures in the
collection, jazz and otherwise.

00:00:43.280 --> 00:00:49.610
I want to -- I want you to tell
our viewers what made an impression

00:00:49.610 --> 00:00:50.910
on you?

00:00:50.910 --> 00:00:52.210
What resonated?

00:00:52.210 --> 00:00:54.830
What moved you?

00:00:54.830 --> 00:00:58.240
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider:
It's just for me,

00:00:58.240 --> 00:01:01.860
I love seeing what a
composer puts to paper,

00:01:01.860 --> 00:01:03.620
seeing what their process is,

00:01:03.620 --> 00:01:08.860
imagining the thought
going down on the paper.

00:01:08.860 --> 00:01:12.820
And, you know, for years,
I was a music copyist,

00:01:12.820 --> 00:01:15.880 position:56%
and I still write in pen and pencil.

00:01:15.880 --> 00:01:26.030
And I always enjoyed the -- seeing
maybe even the speed and the --

00:01:26.030 --> 00:01:30.090
the confidence which you can see
somebody put down their ideas or --

00:01:30.090 --> 00:01:34.610 position:56%
The Bartok we looked at today where
you could see -- Actually, you know,

00:01:34.610 --> 00:01:38.700
he was making his own bar lines
down and the score and everything

00:01:38.700 --> 00:01:42.890
and you see he did it from the
hospital, writing concerto for --

00:01:42.890 --> 00:01:44.190
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Orchestra.

00:01:44.190 --> 00:01:45.490
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: -- orchestra.

00:01:45.490 --> 00:01:46.790
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Yeah.

00:01:46.790 --> 00:01:48.090
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: And
yeah, it was just fun.

00:01:48.090 --> 00:01:51.990
And I enjoyed also seeing some
of the letters, because I am one

00:01:51.990 --> 00:01:55.740
of those people that's very
interested in the person

00:01:55.740 --> 00:01:59.950
and the relationships
and everything that makes

00:01:59.950 --> 00:02:02.380
up who they are as a musician.

00:02:02.380 --> 00:02:04.180
I never think even in my own music,

00:02:04.180 --> 00:02:06.050
I don't think of writing
music as music.

00:02:06.050 --> 00:02:12.330
To me, music is a conduit for
life and so knowing and the fact

00:02:12.330 --> 00:02:14.630
that you have these archives
and knowing a little bit

00:02:14.630 --> 00:02:17.190
about these people's lives
through letters and things

00:02:17.190 --> 00:02:18.530
like that just enriches it.

00:02:18.530 --> 00:02:19.830
It's --

00:02:19.830 --> 00:02:21.380
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: When's the
last time you wrote a letter?

00:02:21.380 --> 00:02:23.040
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: An
actual handwritten letter?

00:02:23.040 --> 00:02:25.170
I send postcards and letters still.

00:02:25.170 --> 00:02:26.470
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Oh really?

00:02:26.470 --> 00:02:27.770
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Yeah.

00:02:27.770 --> 00:02:29.070
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Wonderful.

00:02:29.070 --> 00:02:30.370
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider:
I mean, mostly email,

00:02:30.370 --> 00:02:31.940
but if there's somebody I really
want to write something too,

00:02:31.940 --> 00:02:37.010
I'll still put it in a
postcard or a card, yeah.

00:02:37.010 --> 00:02:39.150
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Now
you mention the Bartok.

00:02:39.150 --> 00:02:40.450
That was a commission.

00:02:40.450 --> 00:02:47.020
