00:02:52.760 --> 00:02:54.760 position:56%
for the library's concert this week.

00:02:54.760 --> 00:02:57.910
I want you to tell us a little
bit about that commission.

00:02:57.910 --> 00:02:59.230
Have you finished it?

00:02:59.230 --> 00:03:01.090
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Yes,
yes, I finished, although --

00:03:01.090 --> 00:03:02.570
although, you know,
we're rehearsing.

00:03:02.570 --> 00:03:05.980
And for me, Peter Sellars
years ago --

00:03:05.980 --> 00:03:08.970
Peter Sellars commissioned me
to write something for my band.

00:03:08.970 --> 00:03:10.270
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: The director.

00:03:10.270 --> 00:03:11.570
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Yes.

00:03:11.570 --> 00:03:12.870
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Yeah.

00:03:12.870 --> 00:03:14.170
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider:
Yeah, the director, yes,

00:03:14.170 --> 00:03:15.470
for the Mozart Festival in Vienna.

00:03:15.470 --> 00:03:18.220
And I wrote a piece -- Actually,
we're going to close our concert

00:03:18.220 --> 00:03:20.750
with called Cerulean Skies.

00:03:20.750 --> 00:03:23.510
And when we premiered
it, you know, I was --

00:03:23.510 --> 00:03:27.490 position:56%
You know, it's always a little bit
of a work in progress, so, you know,

00:03:27.490 --> 00:03:29.200
I always end up doing editing.

00:03:29.200 --> 00:03:31.700
So -- And he said, Maria,
the premiere is never quite,

00:03:31.700 --> 00:03:34.240
you know, where it's going to be.

00:03:34.240 --> 00:03:38.070
It's the first act and
then you do, and so,

00:03:38.070 --> 00:03:40.910
I hope we're going
to be okay, you know?

00:03:40.910 --> 00:03:42.890
But it's scary because I did it,

00:03:42.890 --> 00:03:44.390
something that's a
little bit unusual.

00:03:44.390 --> 00:03:47.400
It has different kinds of
gestures and rhythmic things

00:03:47.400 --> 00:03:50.920
that the band is playing that I
am just indicating with my body.

00:03:50.920 --> 00:03:54.680
The piece is called Data
Lords, and it's piece that's

00:03:54.680 --> 00:04:00.100
about this seduction of all of us
through actually the use of music

00:04:00.100 --> 00:04:02.410
and video and all these
things that people --

00:04:02.410 --> 00:04:08.260
that corporations like YouTube
and Google use to draw eyeballs

00:04:08.260 --> 00:04:11.420
so that they can gather
data and turn it into money.

00:04:11.420 --> 00:04:15.740
And these big data companies
I see them that they are now

00:04:15.740 --> 00:04:20.220
like data lords and we
are kind of the serfdom.

00:04:20.220 --> 00:04:22.440
And it's just taking so much.

00:04:22.440 --> 00:04:28.850
It's literally just sucking
the life out of our economy,

00:04:28.850 --> 00:04:35.130
our music economy and also
out of I think a certain --

00:04:35.130 --> 00:04:41.980
It's the total opposite of what we
did today, that thing of looking

00:04:41.980 --> 00:04:47.480 position:56%
at the real thing, the pencil to the
paper, the thing that the paper made

00:04:47.480 --> 00:04:51.710
as opposed to this sort of
plasticized, digitized thing

00:04:51.710 --> 00:04:53.270
that just is churned out.

00:04:53.270 --> 00:04:58.740
It's like force-feeding, you
know, yourself at the, you know,

00:04:58.740 --> 00:05:01.170
the trough or something
like that -- the trough --

00:05:01.170 --> 00:05:02.920
You know the fast food --

00:05:02.920 --> 00:05:06.300
I mean that's how people
are getting their music.

00:05:06.300 --> 00:05:10.640
And so it's this idea that
we're all just giving this away

00:05:10.640 --> 00:05:12.780
and this intelligence of this thing

00:05:12.780 --> 00:05:15.660
because of all this data is
getting bigger and bigger,

00:05:15.660 --> 00:05:18.510
and they know that there
is a point at which

00:05:18.510 --> 00:05:25.120
that intelligence will become more
than ours, that it will know more.

00:05:25.120 --> 00:05:29.150
We're already at the point where
that data turns into knowledge

00:05:29.150 --> 00:05:32.210
about people and disease
or certain things,

00:05:32.210 --> 00:05:35.580
and they don't even really
understand what those things are,

00:05:35.580 --> 00:05:38.900
but that they can predict
things because of all that data.

00:05:38.900 --> 00:05:42.180
So anyway, this is a piece
that has -- It has --

00:05:42.180 --> 00:05:45.830
I don't know if you'd call
it some beauty but seduction,

00:05:45.830 --> 00:05:47.510
but then it kind of overtakes you.

00:05:47.510 --> 00:05:50.170
So there's these gestures
of the band doing

00:05:50.170 --> 00:05:51.950
like [makes musical
sound], you know.

00:05:51.950 --> 00:05:54.260
So we're still -- we're
still getting that, you know.

00:05:54.260 --> 00:05:56.140
It's a little bit of a dance.

00:05:56.140 --> 00:05:58.650 position:56%
