00:26:44.100 --> 00:26:46.580
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: And does
that impact or in what way does

00:26:46.580 --> 00:26:50.570
that impact your aesthetic
or your artistic identity?

00:26:50.570 --> 00:26:51.870
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: You
know, it's so amazing.

00:26:51.870 --> 00:26:54.240
It's like when you --
As you're coming up

00:26:54.240 --> 00:26:58.730
and you're doing things you don't
realize what's impacting you,

00:26:58.730 --> 00:27:01.740
and then you look back
and you start to see?

00:27:01.740 --> 00:27:05.810
And what -- First of all, when I
was a kid, I loved Aaron Copland,

00:27:05.810 --> 00:27:07.110
and I think there was --

00:27:07.110 --> 00:27:09.820
not the modern Aaron Copland
because I didn't know it.

00:27:09.820 --> 00:27:11.120
You know, I knew more

00:27:11.120 --> 00:27:12.560
of the Appalachian spring
and the, you know --

00:27:12.560 --> 00:27:13.860
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Right.

00:27:13.860 --> 00:27:16.480 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: -- but there was
something about the openness of that

00:27:16.480 --> 00:27:20.470
that I related to, the
landscape of things.

00:27:20.470 --> 00:27:24.580
And I've always been -- Even
earlier today, I was telling you

00:27:24.580 --> 00:27:28.720
about my piano teacher, this
extraordinary teacher, Mrs. Butler,

00:27:28.720 --> 00:27:31.080
who had been a stride
pianist in Chicago.

00:27:31.080 --> 00:27:33.460
She was married to
one of the pianists

00:27:33.460 --> 00:27:36.680
from the Glenn Miller
band, her second husband.

00:27:36.680 --> 00:27:39.100
She was also a great
classical pianist,

00:27:39.100 --> 00:27:41.910
and she was a great
organist, red hair with a face

00:27:41.910 --> 00:27:45.400
like Dizzy Gillespie kind
of, you know, very flamboyant

00:27:45.400 --> 00:27:49.260
with rhinestone-studded
glasses, red hair and wore like,

00:27:49.260 --> 00:27:50.710
you know, moo-moo's and, you know.

00:27:50.710 --> 00:27:54.050
She was just an amazing,
amazing woman.

00:27:54.050 --> 00:27:58.550
And my first lesson she taught
me, started teaching me theory.

00:27:58.550 --> 00:28:03.930
And she taught me to understand
why the music I played felt the way

00:28:03.930 --> 00:28:05.230
it felt.

00:28:05.230 --> 00:28:07.750
So the one-four-five
chord would be, here we --

00:28:07.750 --> 00:28:14.020
here we go up the hill back again
home, to show the four going up,

00:28:14.020 --> 00:28:16.580
the five bringing you
back home is tonic.

00:28:16.580 --> 00:28:20.710
She had -- Before that, it was
bright the day with a major triad,

00:28:20.710 --> 00:28:23.170
dark the night with a minor triad.

00:28:23.170 --> 00:28:33.080
So, I've always equated maybe
the visual to music, and I've --

00:28:33.080 --> 00:28:36.790
Much of my music has
been about something.

00:28:36.790 --> 00:28:39.980
And I don't set out to
write about something.

00:28:39.980 --> 00:28:43.850
It's that I start writing,
and before I know it,

00:28:43.850 --> 00:28:48.860
I'm on top of the silo of the
Thompson Farm in Windom, Minnesota,

00:28:48.860 --> 00:28:51.120
and I'm seeing those
beans, and I'm like,

00:28:51.120 --> 00:28:53.280
Oh my god, that feels like that.

00:28:53.280 --> 00:28:59.980
Maybe it's a way to bring back
memory and freeze it into --

00:28:59.980 --> 00:29:03.480
into a new form that
I can relive it.

00:29:03.480 --> 00:29:05.280
It might be that.

00:29:05.280 --> 00:29:12.360
It might be -- Because I
love it like if my band plays

00:29:12.360 --> 00:29:15.750
and whatever it was that
was going into that music.

00:29:15.750 --> 00:29:18.350
Like I say, the idea -- Usually
when the idea first comes,

00:29:18.350 --> 00:29:19.950
it's just a musical idea.

00:29:19.950 --> 00:29:22.080
Then it attaches a
lot of times itself

00:29:22.080 --> 00:29:24.490 position:56%
to a memory or an idea or something.

00:29:24.490 --> 00:29:27.670
And what I love is in the
end when the band plays that

00:29:27.670 --> 00:29:32.750
and I'm standing there conducting
it, and all that imagery is coming

00:29:32.750 --> 00:29:35.360
to me, to the point sometimes
where it makes me cry.

00:29:35.360 --> 00:29:37.240 position:56%
You know, I'm like, wow, I am there.

00:29:37.240 --> 00:29:41.920
It's just so -- such a powerful
attraction to that moment,

00:29:41.920 --> 00:29:47.620
and I don't know why
that's how it clicks

00:29:47.620 --> 00:29:49.450
for me in my head but it does.

00:29:49.450 --> 00:29:54.030
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: I assumed that
you would need to have a detachment

00:29:54.030 --> 00:29:59.010
in order to pay all attention to
detail and performance, and yet,

00:29:59.010 --> 00:30:01.040
I'm hearing that you
get caught up in it.

00:30:01.040 --> 00:30:02.340
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Oh yeah.

00:30:02.340 --> 00:30:03.640
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum:
Just as [inaudible].

00:30:03.640 --> 00:30:04.940
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider:
Very much, very much.

00:30:04.940 --> 00:30:07.350
I mean I am definitely,
you know, detail, you know,

00:30:07.350 --> 00:30:10.950 position:56%
cut of this breath, you know, that's
a little out of tune, you know,

00:30:10.950 --> 00:30:13.940
look at somebody here, you know,
want a little more trumpets.

00:30:13.940 --> 00:30:15.240 position:56%
Can you play that a little smoother?

00:30:15.240 --> 00:30:16.850
There's always that going on.

00:30:16.850 --> 00:30:19.600
But there are moments
that when it's happening,

00:30:19.600 --> 00:30:21.400
you're just -- you
just get lost in it.

00:30:21.400 --> 00:30:25.530
You just say, oh, you
know, yeah, definitely.

00:30:25.530 --> 00:30:27.010
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Did
you study conducting

00:30:27.010 --> 00:30:29.740
or is this something
that happens naturally?

00:30:29.740 --> 00:30:31.040
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: I
studied a little bit.

00:30:31.040 --> 00:30:33.560
I took some lessons in
Minnesota undergrad,

00:30:33.560 --> 00:30:38.860
some classes with the
conducting teacher at Eastman.

00:30:38.860 --> 00:30:41.140
He -- The poor man,
Donald Hunsberger.

00:30:41.140 --> 00:30:44.680
He was charged with teaching
all the jazz musicians how

00:30:44.680 --> 00:30:45.980
to conduct, you know.

00:30:45.980 --> 00:30:47.280
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Poor man.

00:30:47.280 --> 00:30:48.580
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Poor man.

00:30:48.580 --> 00:30:49.880
But I -- It was funny,
recently, I had to conduct --

00:30:49.880 --> 00:30:51.180
Well a few years back, I had

00:30:51.180 --> 00:30:54.380
to conduct the same Paul Chamber
Orchestra, and I called him up.

00:30:54.380 --> 00:30:59.460 position:56%
I said, Don, can I -- You know, it's
years, decades later, Don can I come

00:30:59.460 --> 00:31:01.420
up and have a little
conducting lesson?

00:31:01.420 --> 00:31:02.730
Can we talk about this piece?

00:31:02.730 --> 00:31:06.060 position:56%
And he was just very sweet about it.

00:31:06.060 --> 00:31:11.260
But, you know, conducting my band
is something that just evolved.

00:31:11.260 --> 00:31:16.760
And what is, you know, my band's
playing and I would just --

00:31:16.760 --> 00:31:19.680
You don't need to conduct
a big band in the --

00:31:19.680 --> 00:31:21.380
I mean you need some
of that technique,

00:31:21.380 --> 00:31:24.660
because there are always
moments where you need, you know,

00:31:24.660 --> 00:31:27.560
the little break, the lift,
the rubato, this and that.

00:31:27.560 --> 00:31:30.160
So you need conducting
technique, but it's not the same

00:31:30.160 --> 00:31:33.350
as in an orchestra where the
conductor's kind of the --

00:31:33.350 --> 00:31:35.340 position:56%
You've got a rhythm section usually.

00:31:35.340 --> 00:31:37.160
There's something keeping time.

00:31:37.160 --> 00:31:43.090
For me with -- with my band, it's
more about giving them the picture,

00:31:43.090 --> 00:31:44.780 position:56%
because the trumpets are back there.

00:31:44.780 --> 00:31:46.810
They're not really
hearing the reads.

00:31:46.810 --> 00:31:48.210
Everybody's kind of separate.

00:31:48.210 --> 00:31:51.880
I see myself as a focal
point to keep them focused

00:31:51.880 --> 00:31:56.600
on where the music is so they
don't just get in their part,

00:31:56.600 --> 00:32:00.210
try and go into auto-play,

00:32:00.210 --> 00:32:03.880
because they're not maybe
hearing the pictures so well,

00:32:03.880 --> 00:32:08.220
because it's that --
I'm that picture

00:32:08.220 --> 00:32:11.600
and I'm letting them know,
is this feeling right?

00:32:11.600 --> 00:32:14.150
You know, they can see it in
my body and if something is --

00:32:14.150 --> 00:32:16.090
And I kind of look at
them and I go like that,

00:32:16.090 --> 00:32:17.390
you know, then they get it.

00:32:17.390 --> 00:32:22.670 position:56%
So for me, it's more about sculpting
this thing so that it is emotional,

00:32:22.670 --> 00:32:27.630
that it's not just technically,
yes, I want it technically right,

00:32:27.630 --> 00:32:29.800
because that also helps
bring out the emotion.

00:32:29.800 --> 00:32:35.790
But bringing out the right
crescendo, flavor, you know,

00:32:35.790 --> 00:32:39.150
just the little things that -- that
are going to make me feel like I'm

00:32:39.150 --> 00:32:43.030
on that silo as opposed to, you
know, that it's a good piece --

00:32:43.030 --> 00:32:46.240
good sounding piece
of music, you know.

00:32:46.240 --> 00:32:50.160
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: There's -- I --
I've no doubt that you've seen it.

00:32:50.160 --> 00:32:55.110 position:56%
In fact, many of the viewers of
this will have seen it, but in 1959,

00:32:55.110 --> 00:32:58.040
CBS Broadcast, something
called, The Sound of Miles

00:32:58.040 --> 00:32:59.900
or The Sound of Miles Davis.

00:32:59.900 --> 00:33:04.480
So it's Miles with his quintet,
and then there's an orchestra led

00:33:04.480 --> 00:33:08.790
by Gil Evans, and they did
some of their collaborations.

00:33:08.790 --> 00:33:10.970
And I love watching Gil conduct.

00:33:10.970 --> 00:33:12.270
It's like a --

00:33:12.270 --> 00:33:13.570
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider:
Yeah, it's kind of

00:33:13.570 --> 00:33:14.870
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: -- big bird.

00:33:14.870 --> 00:33:16.170
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Yeah, yeah, the
kind of long hands and the arms --

00:33:16.170 --> 00:33:17.470
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Yeah.

00:33:17.470 --> 00:33:18.770
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: -- and it's
-- Yeah, they're something.

00:33:18.770 --> 00:33:20.070
It's some about Gil, yeah.

00:33:20.070 --> 00:33:21.370
It's just his movement.

00:33:21.370 --> 00:33:23.070 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: We should talk
a little bit about Gil because along

00:33:23.070 --> 00:33:28.220
with Bob Brookmeyer, Gil Evans
is the musician, arranger,

00:33:28.220 --> 00:33:31.590
composer of who -- who
you're often associated with.

00:33:31.590 --> 00:33:34.260
I love the story about how
you first came to meet Gil.

00:33:34.260 --> 00:33:35.560
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Yeah.

00:33:35.560 --> 00:33:36.860
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum:
Will you tell it?

00:33:36.860 --> 00:33:38.420 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Yeah, so I was
a music copyist in New York eight --

00:33:38.420 --> 00:33:40.630 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: By the way, what
does that mean, a music copyist?

00:33:40.630 --> 00:33:43.430
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider:
Okay, so -- so before --

00:33:43.430 --> 00:33:48.540
before computers back when we were
young with something called and pad

00:33:48.540 --> 00:33:52.510
and ink, and -- Yeah, so this
-- the composer makes the score

00:33:52.510 --> 00:33:55.660
and somebody has to make
all those individual parts

00:33:55.660 --> 00:33:59.060
for all the players, and that
calligraphy is a real art.

00:33:59.060 --> 00:34:02.600
And thank god I had a wonderful
teacher, great composer,

00:34:02.600 --> 00:34:05.830
Dominique Argento, back at
the University of Minnesota.

00:34:05.830 --> 00:34:08.740
And whenever -- And he
taught me orchestration,

00:34:08.740 --> 00:34:12.770
great orchestration
teacher, wow, brilliant.

00:34:12.770 --> 00:34:17.630 position:56%
And all our orchestration exercises,
he made us do in calligraphy pen,

00:34:17.630 --> 00:34:21.820 position:56%
and he said, because that's just
the skill I want you to learn to do.

00:34:21.820 --> 00:34:26.330 position:56%
Well, it was so fantastic because by
the time I left Eastman and I wanted

00:34:26.330 --> 00:34:29.200
to move to New York, I had a skill.

00:34:29.200 --> 00:34:31.630
And so there's these
music copying offices.

00:34:31.630 --> 00:34:32.930
There were.

00:34:32.930 --> 00:34:34.560
We looked at one of
the things today.

00:34:34.560 --> 00:34:35.860
It was a --

00:34:35.860 --> 00:34:37.160
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Charlap?

00:34:37.160 --> 00:34:39.560
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Yeah, Bill --
not Bill Charlap -- Emile Charlap.

00:34:39.560 --> 00:34:43.200
It was a -- it was a -- was
a Brookmeyer score and --

00:34:43.200 --> 00:34:44.500
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Yeah.

00:34:44.500 --> 00:34:45.800
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: -- and on the
bottom of the page, I said, oh,

00:34:45.800 --> 00:34:47.710
I want to see who copied this,
and it was Emile Charlap.

00:34:47.710 --> 00:34:50.540
So his office was right around
the corner, all in mid-town.

00:34:50.540 --> 00:34:54.390
In that -- in that office
at one time, you know,

00:34:54.390 --> 00:34:56.720
all the arrangers sat
there, the copyists.

00:34:56.720 --> 00:34:58.450
It was a music production.

00:34:58.450 --> 00:35:00.020
You know, they had somebody,

00:35:00.020 --> 00:35:01.880
Ray Charles making a
record or something.

00:35:01.880 --> 00:35:03.770
They were sitting there all
writing these arrangements.

00:35:03.770 --> 00:35:05.510
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Like a
factory or an assembly line.

00:35:05.510 --> 00:35:07.410
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Well that
whole area was like that.

00:35:07.410 --> 00:35:08.710
The Brill --

00:35:08.710 --> 00:35:10.010
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Yeah.

00:35:10.010 --> 00:35:11.310
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Have you read
that book, The Brill Building --

00:35:11.310 --> 00:35:12.610
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Yeah.

00:35:12.610 --> 00:35:13.910
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: --
the book about, yeah,

00:35:13.910 --> 00:35:15.210
music in the air or whatever.

00:35:15.210 --> 00:35:16.510 position:56%
It's just -- There was a time there.

00:35:16.510 --> 00:35:17.810
Wow. It must have been amazing.

00:35:17.810 --> 00:35:19.110
So --

00:35:19.110 --> 00:35:20.410
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: So you came
at the tail-end of that time?

00:35:20.410 --> 00:35:21.710
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Well yeah,

00:35:21.710 --> 00:35:24.000
I would say a little past the
tail-end, but there were still,

00:35:24.000 --> 00:35:27.470
yeah -- 1985, there were
still music copying offices,

00:35:27.470 --> 00:35:30.390
and so I got a job in one.

00:35:30.390 --> 00:35:32.550
And I also ran these big --

00:35:32.550 --> 00:35:36.750
You know, they had these huge
Xerox machines for the big scores.

00:35:36.750 --> 00:35:38.580
I miss all that stuff, you know.

00:35:38.580 --> 00:35:41.990
And you'd -- The machine, you
could put the parts through,

00:35:41.990 --> 00:35:45.090
like if you were doing a long
like three page part, you could --

00:35:45.090 --> 00:35:47.810
and the -- You know, then
you'd just have to fold it.

00:35:47.810 --> 00:35:50.090
You didn't have to print
all the individual pages.

00:35:50.090 --> 00:35:51.390
It was amazing.

00:35:51.390 --> 00:35:54.350
So one day this composer,
Tom Pierson came in,

00:35:54.350 --> 00:35:57.630
wanted me to print
a score for him --

00:35:57.630 --> 00:36:00.490 position:56%
was kind of a dance classical thing.

00:36:00.490 --> 00:36:06.060
And he -- and I got talking
and I was really starved

00:36:06.060 --> 00:36:08.090
for conversation about music.

00:36:08.090 --> 00:36:09.390
I'd left Eastman, you know.

00:36:09.390 --> 00:36:12.820
Every night at dinner, we're
talking and now I live in New York,

00:36:12.820 --> 00:36:19.540
and all that community of minds
always churning out over music,

00:36:19.540 --> 00:36:21.100
you know, I just wasn't with that.

00:36:21.100 --> 00:36:28.630 position:56%
So, I think he and I got together
for lunch after that I was on my way

00:36:28.630 --> 00:36:32.920
out to mail something or -- Anyway,
we got talking, and he asked me

00:36:32.920 --> 00:36:37.770
who my favorite writers were,
and I started talking about Gil.

00:36:37.770 --> 00:36:39.070
And he just listened.

00:36:39.070 --> 00:36:41.320
And then we went to a
Penderecki concert I remember.

00:36:41.320 --> 00:36:43.940
But that night, he was
talking about Penderecki.

00:36:43.940 --> 00:36:47.120
He didn't even mention
much about Gil.

00:36:47.120 --> 00:36:49.380
And then he called me and he
said, I didn't tell you today,

00:36:49.380 --> 00:36:52.580
but Gil happens to be
like my closest friend.

00:36:52.580 --> 00:36:54.850
And I called him, and
I told him about you,

00:36:54.850 --> 00:36:58.400
and he needs somebody
to do some work for him.

00:36:58.400 --> 00:37:02.880
And what's crazy about
it is I was so into Gil.

00:37:02.880 --> 00:37:07.350
And Gil was the one that
really -- Gil and Brookmeyer --

00:37:07.350 --> 00:37:10.760
Well, so many of them made me
want to be a jazz composer,

00:37:10.760 --> 00:37:16.510 position:56%
but it really -- Largely, the reason
Gil and Bob were so powerful for me

00:37:16.510 --> 00:37:20.570
that way was that Gil had
-- It's big band music.

00:37:20.570 --> 00:37:24.540
It's jazz, you know, but it had
all that transparency, the nuance,

00:37:24.540 --> 00:37:26.200
the stuff starting with
the Claude Thornhill.

00:37:26.200 --> 00:37:27.520
We looked at the Arab --

00:37:27.520 --> 00:37:28.820
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Arab --

00:37:28.820 --> 00:37:32.000
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: -- Dance
score from the Claude Thornhill.

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:36.100
That music, you know, back then,
you know, it's like big bands were

00:37:36.100 --> 00:37:39.970
like this thing, and then it's
got this airy sound and mixing it

00:37:39.970 --> 00:37:42.580
with classical and I love that.

00:37:42.580 --> 00:37:46.530
And then Bob Brookmeyer had
the thing of forms, you know,

00:37:46.530 --> 00:37:49.170
forms that you find
in classical music.

00:37:49.170 --> 00:37:53.440 position:56%
So bringing together -- So it wasn't
just this definable jazz thing,

00:37:53.440 --> 00:37:54.740
you know.

00:37:54.740 --> 00:37:58.110
So I was -- Way back then,
this is before I even went

00:37:58.110 --> 00:37:59.930
to Eastman or moved to New York.

00:37:59.930 --> 00:38:04.330 position:56%
One night I was sitting on the couch
and I was listening to Svengali,

00:38:04.330 --> 00:38:07.800
and I was looking at the picture
of Gil on the Priestess album.

00:38:07.800 --> 00:38:09.780
And I had this whole vision --

00:38:09.780 --> 00:38:13.400
like literally, it just kind
of came to me working for Gil.

00:38:13.400 --> 00:38:18.880 position:56%
So when that whole thing happened to
me, I was like, this is just freaky.

00:38:18.880 --> 00:38:21.130
It was -- And the first time I saw,

00:38:21.130 --> 00:38:23.910
I met him with some
rehearsal studio.

00:38:23.910 --> 00:38:25.670
He said, come to the
rehearsal studio.

00:38:25.670 --> 00:38:26.970
I'll meet you.

00:38:26.970 --> 00:38:28.270
I'll give -- They were rehearsing

00:38:28.270 --> 00:38:29.750
and he wanted me to
copy some things.

00:38:29.750 --> 00:38:32.340
He came with like a
little sketch this big --

00:38:32.340 --> 00:38:37.160
this little King brand music with
the whole score on each line,

