I related to so much.

00:42:42.170 --> 00:42:44.340
It's very Midwestern.

00:42:44.340 --> 00:42:48.420
It's very plain spoken
but profoundly beautiful.

00:42:48.420 --> 00:42:51.580
And what I discovered is, you know,

00:42:51.580 --> 00:42:55.390
I've been writing instrumental
music for so many years.

00:42:55.390 --> 00:43:00.320
And you're pulling every idea,
and if there is that story.

00:43:00.320 --> 00:43:02.160
Everything's coming out of you.

00:43:02.160 --> 00:43:04.320
Suddenly, when I was
working with this poetry,

00:43:04.320 --> 00:43:08.220
the poetry was giving
me the imagery.

00:43:08.220 --> 00:43:16.550
The poetry was giving me the rhythm
of the, you know, of the words

00:43:16.550 --> 00:43:20.970
and even hinting at where
that melody would want to go.

00:43:20.970 --> 00:43:25.080
So, it was almost like somebody
taking my hand and say, okay,

00:43:25.080 --> 00:43:26.960
this is the basic outline.

00:43:26.960 --> 00:43:29.210
This is the sketch, you know.

00:43:29.210 --> 00:43:30.510
It -- I don't know.

00:43:30.510 --> 00:43:34.820
It just -- It needed -- I don't
want to say the word is easy,

00:43:34.820 --> 00:43:41.900
but it just -- it made it less
effortful, you know, or something.

00:43:41.900 --> 00:43:44.130
There was just something
about it that it just came --

00:43:44.130 --> 00:43:46.710
It felt like somebody just
giving you a little --

00:43:46.710 --> 00:43:49.800
a little boost into
a direction and --

00:43:49.800 --> 00:43:53.660
