of how you might write
for a specific soloist?

00:51:14.750 --> 00:51:17.870
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: I don't
think I can give you an example

00:51:17.870 --> 00:51:19.170
and I'll tell you why.

00:51:19.170 --> 00:51:20.830
So people always say
this about Ellington --

00:51:20.830 --> 00:51:22.130
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Yeah.

00:51:22.130 --> 00:51:23.430
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: It's
probably the most talked

00:51:23.430 --> 00:51:24.730
about aspect of Ellington.

00:51:24.730 --> 00:51:27.220
He wrote for his players
and what I --

00:51:27.220 --> 00:51:34.270
what I would say about
that is that you --

00:51:34.270 --> 00:51:42.730
If you work with people night
after night and year after year,

00:51:42.730 --> 00:51:44.990
you can't help but do that.

00:51:44.990 --> 00:51:47.980
You have a way of relating
and taking them

00:51:47.980 --> 00:51:50.180
in with what you put out.

00:51:50.180 --> 00:51:52.910
It's very much like conversation.

00:51:52.910 --> 00:51:54.560
You're talking to me one way.

00:51:54.560 --> 00:51:57.500
If your mother was sitting here,
you'd talk to her a different way.

00:51:57.500 --> 00:52:00.210
If a -- your closest
friend was sitting here,

00:52:00.210 --> 00:52:03.570
you'd maybe have a highly
inappropriate conversation

00:52:03.570 --> 00:52:05.040
about something, you know.

00:52:05.040 --> 00:52:06.340
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum:
We could do that.

00:52:06.340 --> 00:52:08.110
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Who
-- who knows what --

00:52:08.110 --> 00:52:09.410
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Yeah.

00:52:09.410 --> 00:52:10.710
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider:
-- what it would be?

00:52:10.710 --> 00:52:13.120
And so it's the same
thing, you know.

00:52:13.120 --> 00:52:16.680
It's just your gut
makes you do something.

00:52:16.680 --> 00:52:20.380
So, I don't know if I
can put it into words.

00:52:20.380 --> 00:52:27.490
And maybe sometimes now though I
think I really write for my soloist

00:52:27.490 --> 00:52:32.880
and tuned into what they do, I also
know that sometimes maybe I kind

00:52:32.880 --> 00:52:37.580
of typecast them, because I have an
idea in my head about who they are

00:52:37.580 --> 00:52:41.150
and sometimes for fun, you know,
we'll be on a tour and I'll switch

00:52:41.150 --> 00:52:43.050
around solos to shake things up.

00:52:43.050 --> 00:52:46.680 position:56%
And it's like, okay, let's give this
to this person tonight or whatever.

00:52:46.680 --> 00:52:48.680
And an instrument and a person

00:52:48.680 --> 00:52:51.800
that I never imagined playing
a certain solo will do it,

00:52:51.800 --> 00:52:53.720
and all of a sudden, it
turns it into something

00:52:53.720 --> 00:52:57.650
that I just never imagined
that I love.

00:52:57.650 --> 00:53:04.480
And so -- so, yeah, to say
an example of how I do it;

00:53:04.480 --> 00:53:08.760
well Scott Robinson
-- Let's pick Scott.

00:53:08.760 --> 00:53:14.560
Scott can do so many things with
his instrument, and he is somebody

00:53:14.560 --> 00:53:17.550
who is coming from a deep respect

00:53:17.550 --> 00:53:20.750
of everything very
traditional all the way

00:53:20.750 --> 00:53:24.200
to Sun Ra and beyond, you know.

00:53:24.200 --> 00:53:27.700
So -- so he's got this wide scope.

00:53:27.700 --> 00:53:35.930 position:56%
So with Scott, you know that you can
do things that don't just require,

00:53:35.930 --> 00:53:39.790
you know, fitting in, you know,
really beautiful melodic way

00:53:39.790 --> 00:53:43.460
to a harmonic thing, but that
can go kind of creatively beyond

00:53:43.460 --> 00:53:45.770
into sort of a sonic spectrum.

00:53:45.770 --> 00:53:48.980
I mean there's that, but
then also kind of knowing too

00:53:48.980 --> 00:53:52.230
where his heart can go
as a musician too --

00:53:52.230 --> 00:53:56.380
what he can get into and
what he might not get into.

00:53:56.380 --> 00:53:58.880
So I try to hit that.

00:53:58.880 --> 00:54:01.620 position:56%
For me, the hardest part with all --

00:54:01.620 --> 00:54:05.940
with the guys and this stuff is
when we're rehearsing and trying

00:54:05.940 --> 00:54:11.760
to describe to them in rehearsal
what I want, so that we can get it

00:54:11.760 --> 00:54:14.550
to a certain point so
that then they get it,

00:54:14.550 --> 00:54:17.270
and then now they can take
it to their own point.

00:54:17.270 --> 00:54:22.150 position:56%
But that first initial thing of,
no, no, no, can you try it this way?

00:54:22.150 --> 00:54:23.450
Can you do that?

00:54:23.450 --> 00:54:27.420
You know, it -- it can be very
antithetical to creativity

00:54:27.420 --> 00:54:32.590
and you have to just kind of muscle
it into some sort of understanding

00:54:32.590 --> 00:54:36.660 position:56%
and then -- then the thing freeze
up and then they take it some place.

00:54:36.660 --> 00:54:37.960
I don't know.

00:54:37.960 --> 00:54:39.780
I wasn't expecting.

00:54:39.780 --> 00:54:41.840
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: There
are some very creative people

00:54:41.840 --> 00:54:43.140
in your orchestra.

00:54:43.140 --> 00:54:44.440
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Oh yeah.

00:54:44.440 --> 00:54:45.740
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum:
Because you mentioned Scott.

00:54:45.740 --> 00:54:50.700 position:56%
He not only has this wide palate of
what he's likely to do as a creator,

00:54:50.700 --> 00:54:53.450
but he also has all
these instruments --

00:54:53.450 --> 00:54:54.750
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Yeah.

00:54:54.750 --> 00:54:56.050
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum:
-- they can create on.

00:54:56.050 --> 00:54:57.350
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Yes.

00:54:57.350 --> 00:54:58.650
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: And I
wondered if you ever write

00:54:58.650 --> 00:54:59.950
for a contrabass saxophone?

00:54:59.950 --> 00:55:01.250
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Yes.

00:55:01.250 --> 00:55:02.550
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: You do?

00:55:02.550 --> 00:55:03.850
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Yeah, yeah.

00:55:03.850 --> 00:55:05.150
Sometimes -- Well, you
know what, if I do that --

00:55:05.150 --> 00:55:06.450
Well contrabass clarinet
is in the Bulerias.

00:55:06.450 --> 00:55:10.270
I generally don't do
it as a -- as --

00:55:10.270 --> 00:55:13.780
I do it as this could possibly
be played on this also,

00:55:13.780 --> 00:55:17.640
because getting a contrabass
saxophone on an airplane,

00:55:17.640 --> 00:55:21.500
you know -- There are -- there are
practicalities that you have to --

00:55:21.500 --> 00:55:25.000
So, we'll experiment
with those things

00:55:25.000 --> 00:55:28.640
and contrabass trombone,
George Flynn.

00:55:28.640 --> 00:55:31.860
But I love when Scott brings
out these wild instruments,

00:55:31.860 --> 00:55:33.660
you know, and plays things.

00:55:33.660 --> 00:55:36.920 position:56%
I just -- I love it and the audience
loves it, and it's just so --

00:55:36.920 --> 00:55:38.530
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: It's
visually interesting also --

00:55:38.530 --> 00:55:39.830
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Yeah, yeah.

00:55:39.830 --> 00:55:41.130
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: --
to watch your orchestra.

00:55:41.130 --> 00:55:46.330
I suppose I should ask you
about your brush with one

00:55:46.330 --> 00:55:52.000
of the most famous,
let's say rock icons,

00:55:52.000 --> 00:55:54.420
and that's David Bowie
at the end of his life.

00:55:54.420 --> 00:55:55.720
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Yeah.

00:55:55.720 --> 00:55:57.380
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Why don't
you talk a little bit about what

00:55:57.380 --> 00:56:01.840
that experience meant to
you and how it played out?

00:56:01.840 --> 00:56:03.140
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider:
Well, I'll tell you.

00:56:03.140 --> 00:56:06.940
The biggest way, it's -- I
mean it's how it's played.

00:56:06.940 --> 00:56:09.650
This piece that I wrote
for you, for the Library

00:56:09.650 --> 00:56:11.400
of Congress would not
have been written

00:56:11.400 --> 00:56:13.130
if it weren't for David Bowie.

00:56:13.130 --> 00:56:14.430
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Really?

00:56:14.430 --> 00:56:15.730
How so?

00:56:15.730 --> 00:56:17.540
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: There
is no question about that.

00:56:17.540 --> 00:56:20.630
Well, so he came to me
about working on this song

00:56:20.630 --> 00:56:22.740
that he was -- had started.

00:56:22.740 --> 00:56:27.360
He gave -- he came with
a, like a little recording

00:56:27.360 --> 00:56:28.660
of something he had put together.

00:56:28.660 --> 00:56:31.520
It was the beginnings of
something, but it wasn't developed

00:56:31.520 --> 00:56:33.090
into this long thing and --

00:56:33.090 --> 00:56:34.390
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum:
And he knew about you

00:56:34.390 --> 00:56:35.690
or did you know each other already?

00:56:35.690 --> 00:56:36.990
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider:
No, I'd never met him,

00:56:36.990 --> 00:56:38.760
but he had come to hear the band.

00:56:38.760 --> 00:56:40.060
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Got it.

00:56:40.060 --> 00:56:41.360
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: And somebody
had once written to me about,

00:56:41.360 --> 00:56:42.910
you know, would you sign some CDs?

00:56:42.910 --> 00:56:44.500
I want to give them to
David for this birthday.

00:56:44.500 --> 00:56:48.090 position:56%
So I knew David liked my music, that
he came to hear the band one night,

00:56:48.090 --> 00:56:51.270
and he was gone before the
-- I had a chance to say, hi.

00:56:51.270 --> 00:56:55.450
And then out of the blue, I'd
heard he was looking for --

00:56:55.450 --> 00:57:00.810 position:56%
for me, and he called me about
collaborating on this song together.

00:57:00.810 --> 00:57:06.320
And I was very, very nervous
about it, because I just --

00:57:06.320 --> 00:57:08.090
It's like David Bowie,
and I just thought,

00:57:08.090 --> 00:57:12.630
what if I don't meet his
expectation or you know?

00:57:12.630 --> 00:57:15.970 position:56%
So I kept saying to him, okay, you
just have to promise me if you don't

00:57:15.970 --> 00:57:17.270
like it, you can just say so.

00:57:17.270 --> 00:57:18.570
That's okay, you know.

00:57:18.570 --> 00:57:20.390
I was just constantly doing that.

00:57:20.390 --> 00:57:23.920
And then once we were --
decided we were going to go ahead

00:57:23.920 --> 00:57:27.880
and I listened to the thing and
he was sitting there, you know,

00:57:27.880 --> 00:57:30.250
and I heard it, and I
went over to the piano,

00:57:30.250 --> 00:57:31.550
and I started playing around.

00:57:31.550 --> 00:57:34.150
And I said, so you
want this to be dark?

00:57:34.150 --> 00:57:36.060
Because I said this doesn't
sound super dark to me.

00:57:36.060 --> 00:57:37.940
He said, I want it dark.

00:57:37.940 --> 00:57:41.480
And so I was playing
around, and I said, okay.

00:57:41.480 --> 00:57:42.780
I said, I'll do it.

00:57:42.780 --> 00:57:45.690
I said, let's -- I think I hear
-- I said, I don't want to say,

00:57:45.690 --> 00:57:49.450
yes unless I feel like I can
really bring something to it.

00:57:49.450 --> 00:57:51.420
Of course, who doesn't want
to work with David Bowie?

00:57:51.420 --> 00:57:55.470 position:56%
But I didn't want to work with David
Bowie unless I felt like I was going

00:57:55.470 --> 00:57:56.890
to do something he was
going to be happy with.

00:57:56.890 --> 00:58:01.270
So -- so then I worked on
some ideas or, you know,

00:58:01.270 --> 00:58:02.720
we talked about a little bit.

00:58:02.720 --> 00:58:04.150
He left and then he came back.

00:58:04.150 --> 00:58:06.560
And then I brought some
ideas to the table.

00:58:06.560 --> 00:58:09.620
Then we started working together
on it, and we met a few times,

00:58:09.620 --> 00:58:11.460
and we put together
a little session.

00:58:11.460 --> 00:58:13.780
But somewhere in there, you
know, I was like, David,

00:58:13.780 --> 00:58:15.250
this is going to be
really expensive.

00:58:15.250 --> 00:58:17.700
What we're doing is
kind of a crazy thing.

00:58:17.700 --> 00:58:19.290
And what if it's not good?

00:58:19.290 --> 00:58:20.590
What if you don't like it?

00:58:20.590 --> 00:58:22.560
And he said, Maria,
the plane goes down.

00:58:22.560 --> 00:58:24.560
He said, everybody walks away.

00:58:24.560 --> 00:58:25.860
So -- so --

00:58:25.860 --> 00:58:27.160
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Yeah.

00:58:27.160 --> 00:58:29.670
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: You know and
I'm a person who I go in a crisis.

00:58:29.670 --> 00:58:31.790
When people call me
to do a commission,

00:58:31.790 --> 00:58:33.120
many composers are happy.

00:58:33.120 --> 00:58:36.890
I'm like, oh, no, not a commission,
because I know I'm going to --

00:58:36.890 --> 00:58:38.630
That means I'm going
to torture myself.

00:58:38.630 --> 00:58:41.510
I'm going to have several
months of self-loathing.

00:58:41.510 --> 00:58:42.810
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Is that true?

00:58:42.810 --> 00:58:44.110
Are you really like this?

00:58:44.110 --> 00:58:45.410
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Absolutely.

00:58:45.410 --> 00:58:46.820 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: But that doesn't
come from insecurity, does it?

00:58:46.820 --> 00:58:48.120
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Of course.

00:58:48.120 --> 00:58:49.420
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Really?

00:58:49.420 --> 00:58:50.720
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Deep-seated --

00:58:50.720 --> 00:58:52.020 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: I would not have
imagined you as an insecure person.

00:58:52.020 --> 00:58:53.320 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Are you serious?

00:58:53.320 --> 00:58:57.560
Oh, yeah. When it comes to the
writing and everything, oh yeah.

00:58:57.560 --> 00:58:58.860
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum:
And it's every time?

00:58:58.860 --> 00:59:01.060
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Oh, I have
-- I have -- Every time I hear --

00:59:01.060 --> 00:59:02.360
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Wow.

00:59:02.360 --> 00:59:03.660
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: -- new
music, I go in a crisis

00:59:03.660 --> 00:59:07.160
and many times have been in tears
at rehearsals including yesterday.

00:59:07.160 --> 00:59:08.870
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum:
Who'd of thought?

00:59:08.870 --> 00:59:10.660
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Yeah,
it can happen to me.

00:59:10.660 --> 00:59:12.540
Yeah, I just get frustrated.

00:59:12.540 --> 00:59:15.270
It's hard for me to
figure it all out.

00:59:15.270 --> 00:59:17.270
Every time, it is so --

00:59:17.270 --> 00:59:18.830
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: But
Bowie gave you some cues

00:59:18.830 --> 00:59:21.210 position:56%
that said that, yes, she hears it --

00:59:21.210 --> 00:59:22.590
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: It's okay.

00:59:22.590 --> 00:59:23.890
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Yeah.

00:59:23.890 --> 00:59:27.100
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: So when
I was writing this piece,

00:59:27.100 --> 00:59:29.120
and David liked my intense stuff.

00:59:29.120 --> 00:59:31.670
So he wanted this piece
to be kind of a Sue.

00:59:31.670 --> 00:59:34.210
It ended up being called Sue
or In the Season of Crime.

00:59:34.210 --> 00:59:38.610 position:56%
He wanted this drum and bass fast,
kind of drums going under this thing

00:59:38.610 --> 00:59:41.700
and this whole thing was just
kind of this intense thing.

00:59:41.700 --> 00:59:45.620
And then I created this sort
of rubato stuff over the top.

00:59:45.620 --> 00:59:49.690
Well, somehow that whole
concept has just been in my head,

00:59:49.690 --> 00:59:52.170
and he liked my intense music.

00:59:52.170 --> 00:59:55.100
And as I started working
on this idea,

00:59:55.100 --> 00:59:59.700 position:56%
all of a sudden I just realized this
is a continuation of David -- David.

00:59:59.700 --> 01:00:02.730
And David would really
love this piece.

01:00:02.730 --> 01:00:04.030
I know he would love this piece.

01:00:04.030 --> 01:00:05.660
It might not be quite fully formed.

01:00:05.660 --> 01:00:09.100
I may have to do some editing
yet, but I think he would --

01:00:09.100 --> 01:00:11.220
he would love what I'm doing.

01:00:11.220 --> 01:00:14.510
My assistant Marie, she was at the
rehearsal when I was playing it.

01:00:14.510 --> 01:00:15.990
She said, "David would love this."

01:00:15.990 --> 01:00:17.550
And I said, "Yeah,
I think he would,"

01:00:17.550 --> 01:00:19.520
which makes me happy, you know.

01:00:19.520 --> 01:00:24.760
And I -- So these gestures
that I do in the ensemble

01:00:24.760 --> 01:00:27.440
where the band just
goes -- the band --

01:00:27.440 --> 01:00:29.990
the rhythm section's
cooking along and there's --

01:00:29.990 --> 01:00:32.020
the soloist is going or whatever

01:00:32.020 --> 01:00:33.500
and the band just starts
going [makes musical noise].

01:00:33.500 --> 01:00:36.110
That's the kind of thing.

01:00:36.110 --> 01:00:40.780
I would've just -- I don't know if
I would've ever risked doing it.

01:00:40.780 --> 01:00:44.170
And I -- When I threw it in front
of my band, it was just like,

01:00:44.170 --> 01:00:45.470
I'm just going to do this.

01:00:45.470 --> 01:00:46.770
The plane goes down, whatever.

01:00:46.770 --> 01:00:48.070
We do all walk away.

01:00:48.070 --> 01:00:49.370
You know, that's art.

01:00:49.370 --> 01:00:53.670
We take the risk and we try
it and we see what happens.

01:00:53.670 --> 01:00:58.960
And so, I did this piece with --
Even though I will tell you, yes,

01:00:58.960 --> 01:01:04.630
it's been stressful, I did it
with more joy and more like,

01:01:04.630 --> 01:01:07.210
throw it to the wind,
see what happens,

01:01:07.210 --> 01:01:10.010
than I would've because of him.

01:01:10.010 --> 01:01:14.740 position:56%
And I kept having his face in my
head of him just smiling and that --

01:01:14.740 --> 01:01:18.570
I still remember him looking, you
know, just smiling and just --

01:01:18.570 --> 01:01:21.600
And at the -- and when we were
recording, seeing his face

01:01:21.600 --> 01:01:23.810
through the glass and just smiling,

01:01:23.810 --> 01:01:26.300
just enjoying doing this
thing with the band.

01:01:26.300 --> 01:01:30.160
You just -- You know, he
loved Kenton, loved Kenton.

01:01:30.160 --> 01:01:31.460
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum:
Oh, I didn't know.

01:01:31.460 --> 01:01:32.760
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Yeah.

01:01:32.760 --> 01:01:34.460
And he loved jazz and
he loved big band music,

01:01:34.460 --> 01:01:37.620
and then his last album
ended up being with Donny.

01:01:37.620 --> 01:01:38.920
So --

01:01:38.920 --> 01:01:40.220
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Donny McCaslin.

01:01:40.220 --> 01:01:41.520
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Yeah.

01:01:41.520 --> 01:01:42.820
He had wanted to do one
more piece with me --

01:01:42.820 --> 01:01:44.120
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Yeah.

01:01:44.120 --> 01:01:48.230 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: -- and we talked
even about doing much more, but --

01:01:48.230 --> 01:01:50.420
and I think we would've
done much more.

01:01:50.420 --> 01:01:52.310
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Did you know
at the time that he was dying?

01:01:52.310 --> 01:01:54.650
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: No, no.

01:01:54.650 --> 01:01:57.230
But -- but I didn't have
time to do another piece,

01:01:57.230 --> 01:02:00.260
because I was doing the Thompson
Fields, my newest record, so --

01:02:00.260 --> 01:02:04.130 position:56%
And I -- and I didn't even have time
for Sue, but I did it, you know,

01:02:04.130 --> 01:02:08.060
but that summer was just so
cramped and busy and stressful.

01:02:08.060 --> 01:02:11.520
And so I just said I just
only have the time for one,

01:02:11.520 --> 01:02:14.890
but the other piece ended
up becoming Lazarus.

01:02:14.890 --> 01:02:17.050
And I'm so glad that they did it.

01:02:17.050 --> 01:02:18.350
And I had said to him.

01:02:18.350 --> 01:02:21.800 position:56%
I -- When he was describing to me
the whole drum and bass and the jazz

01:02:21.800 --> 01:02:24.560
and everything, I said, you have
to listen to Donny McCaslin.

01:02:24.560 --> 01:02:26.150
I -- So I said, let me get --

01:02:26.150 --> 01:02:28.050
I pulled out, you know,
the recordings I have.

01:02:28.050 --> 01:02:29.350
I said, listen to this.

01:02:29.350 --> 01:02:30.650
And he just loved it.

01:02:30.650 --> 01:02:32.750
I said, you should
work with these guys.

01:02:32.750 --> 01:02:34.050
This would be amazing.

01:02:34.050 --> 01:02:36.730
This would be an unbelievable
combination.

01:02:36.730 --> 01:02:41.570
And we went to hear Donny and Tony
Visconte was there, his producer,

01:02:41.570 --> 01:02:47.610 position:56%
and they ended up with Donny's group
doing that last album which for me,

01:02:47.610 --> 01:02:49.680
is one of the greatest
albums David made.

01:02:49.680 --> 01:02:50.980
It's so beautiful.

01:02:50.980 --> 01:02:52.820
It is so evocative.

01:02:52.820 --> 01:02:56.270
I love it so much, but then I'm
just wrecked after I listen to it.

01:02:56.270 --> 01:03:01.270
So I -- Then I can't listen to it
that last -- the last song on that.

01:03:01.270 --> 01:03:02.570
Oh my god.

01:03:02.570 --> 01:03:04.140
It's so beautiful.

01:03:04.140 --> 01:03:10.170
So I love what David and
I created together on Sue.

01:03:10.170 --> 01:03:11.470
I love it.

01:03:11.470 --> 01:03:12.830
I love the way he sings on it.

01:03:12.830 --> 01:03:14.720
I'm so happy with it.

01:03:14.720 --> 01:03:19.380
But even if all that had been was
just to get him connected to Donny

01:03:19.380 --> 01:03:23.850
to make that last record,
I would've been like, wow,

01:03:23.850 --> 01:03:25.290
that might be musically one

01:03:25.290 --> 01:03:30.030
of the greatest things I ever
did is just being that, you know,

01:03:30.030 --> 01:03:34.120
little arrow point for him, so.

01:03:34.120 --> 01:03:35.780
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: I'm
glad you both did it.

01:03:35.780 --> 01:03:37.270
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Yeah, it's --

01:03:37.270 --> 01:03:44.740
Who would think that you'd
affect David Bowie's musical --

01:03:44.740 --> 01:03:46.120
last musical project?

01:03:46.120 --> 01:03:49.610 position:56%
Do you know I would've -- I would've
thought I'd be the last person

01:03:49.610 --> 01:03:51.250
on earth that would that, you know.

01:03:51.250 --> 01:03:56.900
But it just goes to show
you how open musicians are,

01:03:56.900 --> 01:04:01.140
how open we are amongst
ourselves and what a world --

01:04:01.140 --> 01:04:03.750
a beautiful world of collaboration.

01:04:03.750 --> 01:04:11.100
I mean it's -- It is the greatest
world to be a part of and it's

01:04:11.100 --> 01:04:14.090
such a privilege, and
there's so much talent.

01:04:14.090 --> 01:04:18.230
And there's so much hard
work and creativity.

01:04:18.230 --> 01:04:21.460
And I think it's -- Going
back to that other subject,

01:04:21.460 --> 01:04:22.760
the nasty subject before,

01:04:22.760 --> 01:04:27.230 position:56%
I think that's why I make this whole
advocacy thing such a huge part

01:04:27.230 --> 01:04:33.340 position:56%
of my life, because it burns my butt
when people not only take advantage

01:04:33.340 --> 01:04:36.990
of the financial aspects of,
you know, of people's lives --

01:04:36.990 --> 01:04:43.290
It's basically like reaching into
somebody's 401K and saying, hey,

01:04:43.290 --> 01:04:47.550
I'm going to give out, you know,
number -- little 15 dollar --

01:04:47.550 --> 01:04:49.770
You know, here, everybody,
take a little, you know

01:04:49.770 --> 01:04:51.620
and just pick away at it.

01:04:51.620 --> 01:04:54.170
It's not just that.

01:04:54.170 --> 01:04:57.820
It's eroding the whole
culture of it.

01:04:57.820 --> 01:05:01.790
And it's going to affect
the quality of the music,

01:05:01.790 --> 01:05:04.400
because if the music can
only then be made just

01:05:04.400 --> 01:05:08.940
by these massive record companies
that are pushing these, you know,

01:05:08.940 --> 01:05:13.600
teen wonders or whatever
it is just to make money

01:05:13.600 --> 01:05:18.440 position:56%
and get billion streams or whatever,
and so many other musicians are just

01:05:18.440 --> 01:05:20.690
like I can't swim amidst
this, you know.

01:05:20.690 --> 01:05:24.740
How can I have a family if I
get a check for three cents

01:05:24.740 --> 01:05:27.310
or 30 dollars even in this day?

01:05:27.310 --> 01:05:30.980
You know I have millions of streams
and got, you know, 17 dollars.

01:05:30.980 --> 01:05:32.280
I mean it's like come one.

01:05:32.280 --> 01:05:34.820
This isn't -- this is -- this
is going to destroy things,

01:05:34.820 --> 01:05:39.760
and it makes me angry
because it's an ecosystem.

01:05:39.760 --> 01:05:43.730
It's an amazing ecosystem,
the music industry.

01:05:43.730 --> 01:05:45.900 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: It's fascinating
to hear you talk about it

01:05:45.900 --> 01:05:50.400
because within you, there's a
kind of balance between the things

01:05:50.400 --> 01:05:54.200
that might arouse your
passion and the things --

01:05:54.200 --> 01:05:56.960
the gifts that you've
been given in life.

01:05:56.960 --> 01:06:00.440
And the greatest thing
is to find that balance.

01:06:00.440 --> 01:06:01.740
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Yeah.

01:06:01.740 --> 01:06:03.040
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Yeah.

01:06:03.040 --> 01:06:04.340
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Not easy.

01:06:04.340 --> 01:06:05.640
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: Yeah.

01:06:05.640 --> 01:06:06.940
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Not easy.

01:06:06.940 --> 01:06:08.240
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: As a --

01:06:08.240 --> 01:06:09.540
I think we have time maybe
for one last question.

01:06:09.540 --> 01:06:10.840
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: Okay.

01:06:10.840 --> 01:06:13.480
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: As a composer,
as an arranger, band leader,

01:06:13.480 --> 01:06:16.310
all the other hyphens, all
the other hats you wear,

01:06:16.310 --> 01:06:19.040
how do you measure success?

01:06:23.850 --> 01:06:26.490
&gt;&gt; Maria Schneider: How
do I measure success?

01:06:26.490 --> 01:06:30.060
I don't know.

01:06:30.060 --> 01:06:36.080
Success to me, enjoying
loving what you do and feeling

01:06:36.080 --> 01:06:39.780
like it's growing and it's moving.

01:06:39.780 --> 01:06:44.200
Because success kind
of implies arrival.

01:06:44.200 --> 01:06:48.370
And artists, I think you never
feel like you arrive, you know.

01:06:48.370 --> 01:06:49.750
Somebody said to me, what --

01:06:49.750 --> 01:06:52.130
Well does it feel good to
get like where you are?

01:06:52.130 --> 01:06:55.670
And I said, No, actually not,
because it's an infinite ways to go

01:06:55.670 --> 01:06:57.340
and you're always a
beginner on the next.

01:06:57.340 --> 01:07:00.160
You know, there's always the
next wrung on the ladder.

01:07:00.160 --> 01:07:04.420
And maybe you get to a certain
point of confidence and, you know,

01:07:04.420 --> 01:07:07.960
not proving yourself
that makes some plateaus,

01:07:07.960 --> 01:07:09.940
but then there's always
that next challenge.

01:07:09.940 --> 01:07:14.830
So, success, you know, I think
if you ever even have the feeling

01:07:14.830 --> 01:07:19.330
of success, you sort
of are done, you know.

01:07:19.330 --> 01:07:24.120
So, maybe success is never
actually feeling success.

01:07:24.120 --> 01:07:27.660
I don't know -- I don't know.

01:07:27.660 --> 01:07:29.030
&gt;&gt; Larry Appelbaum: A
snake eating its tail --

